@NODE "Running CrossMAC from the Product Disk"
Double-Clicking  on  the  appropriate  icon can start CrossMAC from
the  product  disk  (particularly  if  you  are running on a floppy
based system).

To  start:  double-click  on  the "MAC0" icon. Your internal floppy
drive  will  now  be  configured  as  a  Mac  drive  with  the name
"MAC0:".  You  can  now  read  and  write the different Mac formats
which  your  System hardware will allow. For the different types of
formats  supported  and  the hardware requirements for some formats
please see @{"Formats Supported" link "Formats_Supported"}.

To  format  a  Mac  disk,  double-click  on  the @{b}Format@{ub} icon in the
@{i}System@{ui}  drawer.  Choose  the  device to format from the device list
and answer any of the questions and options given.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Installing CrossMAC"
Simply  clicking  the  Install  icon  from Workbench will begin the
installation  of  the CrossMAC FileSystem. If you are installing to
a  hard  drive,  some  of  the  files must be copied to your System
partition.  Only  FileSystem  related  files  are  copied  to  your
System  partition,  you  may select the destination of the CrossMAC
utilities,   if   you   are   installing  them.  The  install  uses
Commodore's   Installer,   so   if   you   have   installed   other
applications  that  use  the  Installer,  the environment should be
familiar to you.

Once  installed,  you  can  use  most  features  immediately. A few
features  such  as  Mac  hard  disk  access  may require additional
operations  be  performed  before  use. For further information see
@{"Configuring a Mac Hard Drive" link "Configuring a Mac Hard Drive"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Manual Corrections"

@{b}Finder_Manager is now File_Type_Manager@{ub}

References  to  @{i}Finder_Manager@{ui}  in  the  manual  should be replaced
with  @{i}File_Type_Manager@{ui}.  We  realized  after  the  manual  went to
print   that   the   term  "Finder"  may  be  a  trademarked  name.
Consequently  we  have  changed  the  name  of the program to avoid
possible  legal  hassles.  Please remember this change of name when
reading the manual.

