Our secondary address is cstron@m-net.arbornet.org
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Screen Blinks"
@{b}"My  screen  blinks  when reading or writing Mac 800K disks. What's
happening?"@{ub}

If  you  get  this phenomemon, don't panic. It's not fatal. Only if
you  have  EVERY  element  of  the following setup might the screen
blinks occur:

    · Amax II or AMax IV card
    · Reading/writing 800K Mac low density disks

Due  to  the design of the AMax cards, we need to temporarily
shut  down  the screen DMA hardware to reduce the chance of missing
data  from  the floppy controller onboard the AMax card. This means
screen  updates  will  be  shut down temporarily. We also recommend
that  you  you  don't  perform  any  high-speed  serial port access
during  those  times  either.  This  only applies when accessing an
800K Mac disk.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Renaming Files"
Just  a  short  note  about  renaming  files  under this version of
CrossMAC:  Although  the Amiga treats the data and resource `forks'
as  separate  files  the  Mac  likes  to  keep  them together. As a
compromise, we've tried to do both.

If   you   rename  either  the  data  or  resource  file,  it  will
automatically rename the other.
@ENDNODE



@NODE "Configuring a Mac Hard Drive"
CrossMAC can support Mac formatted hard drives.

To   configure  a  Mac  Hard  Disk,  use  our  @{i}Install@{ui}  program  or
double-click  the  ConfigDisk.CrossMAC  icon  which  resides on the
product  disk  (if  you're trying to configure a CD-ROM, please see
@{"Configuring a CD-ROM Drive" link "Configuring_a_CD-ROM_Drive"}).    Once    the   program   starts,   a
configuration of one of three types of hard disks is available.

@{b}One:@{ub}  A  'true'  Mac  hard disk configured as the entire disk. This
type   is   useful  to  transfer  data  between  the  Amiga  and  a
stand-alone  Mac.  Examples  of  this  type of disk are SyQuest and
Bernoulli.  We  do  HIGHLY recommend that this type of hard disk be
formatted   on  the  Mac  first  then  brought  to  the  Amiga  for
configuring.
@{"Configure a 'true' Mac hard disk NOW!" SYSTEM "c/Configdisk Mac Disk POSTFIX=0 PREFIX=MHD BUFFERS=40"}

@{b}Two:@{ub}  An  'image'  of  an  Mac  hard disk within an Amiga hard disk
partition.  An  example  of  this  type  of disk is an AMax/EMPLANT
partition.
@{"Configure an 'image' of an Mac hard disk NOW!" SYSTEM "c/Configdisk Mac PARTITION POSTFIX=0 PREFIX=MHD BUFFERS=40"}

@{b}Three:@{ub}  An  'image'  of  an Mac hard disk within a file. An example
of this type of disk is an ShapeShifter or EMPLANT diskfile.
@{"Configure a Mac 'diskfile' NOW!" SYSTEM "c/Configdisk Mac FILE POSTFIX=0 PREFIX=MHD BUFFERS=40"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Configuring_a_CD-ROM_Drive"
To  configure  a  CD-ROM  Drive  to  read  Mac HFS CD-ROMS, use our
@{i}Install@{ui}   program  or  double-click  the  ConfigDisk.CrossMAC_CDROM
icon  which  resides  on  the  product disk. The controller must be
able to support SCSI direct commands with block sizes of 2048.
@{"Configure a Mac CD-ROM drive NOW!" SYSTEM "c/Configdisk Mac Disk POSTFIX=0 PREFIX=MCD BUFFERS=60 SCSI_DIRECT BLOCKSIZE=2048"}

@ENDNODE


@NODE "Formats_Supported"
CrossMAC  supports  a  variety  of  different  floppy disk formats.
Although  CrossMAC  can  read the standard Mac floppy formats given
the  proper  Amiga hardware (see below). CrossMAC can also read and
write  the  formats  created  by  some Mac emulators. The quasi-Mac
formats  supported  are  the  AMax  II  and Emplant disk format for
emulation of 800K floppies.

These  Mac  formats  require certain Amiga hardware before they can
work with CrossMAC.

    · Mac  800K  --  AMax  II cartridge with Mac 800K floppy drive,
      AMax II Plus card or AMax IV card.
    · Mac 1440K or 1.44M -- an Amiga high density floppy drive
    · AMax   or   Emplant   800K  -  standard  Amiga  drives  using
      low-density disks.
    · Mac 800K -- AMIA cartridge with Mac 800K floppy drive.

CrossMAC  can  also  be used on to read Mac hierarchical file
system  (HFS)  CD-ROMS.  Please  see @{"Configuring a CD-ROM Drive" link "Configuring_a_CD-ROM_Drive"} for
setting up a proper mountfile to use HFS CD-ROMS.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MacBinary Support"
CrossMAC support MacBinary files in two ways.

First,  if  you  read  a  file  from a CrossMAC device and append a
`.bin'  to  the  end  of  the name, we'll automatically combine the
data  and  resource  forks into a MacBinary file (type II). Also if
you  move  a  MacBinary  file  to  a CrossMAC device and it has the
`.bin'  appended  to the end, we'll automatically separate the data
and resource forks.

Secondly,  we  support  the  MacBinary  explicitly  by  setting the
`MacBin  Only'  option  in the CrossMAC commodity for the specified
device. The default setting is `Both Forks'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Data Fork Only Mode"
CrossMAC  can  be  configured  to  display  data  forks  only. This
option  will  filter out the resource forks from directory listings
and  Workbench  windows. This is particularly useful to most people
since  the  data  in  the resource fork is rarely used. To activate
this  feature,  select  the  `Data  Fork'  option  in  the CrossMAC
commodity  for  the  specified device. The default setting is `Both
Forks'.

Although  the  resource  forks  do not appear in this mode they can
still  be  accessed.  Adding  the `.rs' to the end of the data name
will access the resource fork if it is present on the disk.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Setting the Default FileType"
You,  our  customers,  have  described  a  need  to save files to a
CrossMAC   disk  with  filetypes  different  than  the  default  of
"TEXT".  In  addition,  some  programs  generating the files do not
allow  the  file  extension  to be user selectable (such as Toaster
framestores).  We  hopefully  addressed  these problems by allowing
the  user  to  set  the  default  filetype  (and  creator)  in  the
File_Type_Manager.

The  File_Type_Manager  now has two string fields where the default
filetype  and  creator can be user selectable. These values will be
used  if  a  file  is  written  to  the  CrossMAC disk and the file
extension  does  not  match  any  listed  in the filetype database.
Note:   The  default  filetype  and  creator  are  global  for  all
CrossMAC devices.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Who Owns This Disk Anyway?"
Don't  worry,  this is not a rehash of the license agreement you've
already  read  on  the  front  of  the disk envelope. This concerns
people  who  are using MAC emulator products on the Amiga. Examples
of emulators are AMAX, EMPLANT or ShapeShifter.

If   you've   configured   a   Mac   disk   for  CrossMAC  that  is
simultaneously  configured  for  one  of the emulators, you may run
into a problem.

The  problem:  When more than one file system tries to write to the
same   physical   disk   volume/partition,  the  disk  may  end  up
corrupted.  Both  CrossMAC  and  the  emulators running Mac OSs are
file systems.

Let  me  draw  a  simple  analogy.  Let's say there is one checking
account  and  you have a set of checks and a friend has another set
of  checks  to the same account. If the both of you never cooperate
to  balance  the  account when checks are written, the account will
eventually be overdrawn.

Similarly,  file  systems  tend to cache small portions of the disk
so  as  to  speed  disk  access.  Let's  suppose  CrossMAC  and the
emulator  (running  Mac  OS)  just  happen  to  cache the same disk
information.  If  CrossMAC  modifies the information it has cached,
the  Mac  (the other file system) will not know the information was
changed.  Now,  CrossMAC  creates  a  new file and uses some blocks
not  previously  used. If the Mac wishes to create a file, it might
reuse  those  blocks  allocated  by CrossMAC. When this happens the
disk  is  most  likely  corrupted since neither file system has the
correct   information.  Both  have  also  modified  the  disk  with
out-of-sync information.

The  solution:  If  both  file systems would cooperate when writing
new  information  to  the  disk,  we'd have our problem solved. For
reasons  which  are  complicated,  that  solution  is not likely to
happen.

You  can  have  as  many  file  systems read the disk as long as no
writing  occurs.  However, if you must write, there are things that
can be done to significantly minimize disk corruption.
    · Create  two  partitions. One for CrossMAC to write to and the
      Mac  to  read  from and the the other for the Mac to write to
      and CrossMAC to read from.
    · Manually  prevent  multiple  file systems from simultaneously
      writing to the disk.
    · After  writing  the  disk  with  the Mac, first drop the disk
      into  the  Mac  trashcan. Next perform a @{b}DiskChg@{ub} (diskchange)
      for  the  CrossMAC  device.  This  action  will flush the Mac
      side and reread the disk from the Amiga side.
    · After  writing  the  disk with CrossMAC, pull the disk out of
      the  Mac  trashcan.  This action will reread the disk for the
      Mac side.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Troubleshooting"
Here  are  some  ideas  to  help  you should you have trouble using
CrossMAC.

@{b}General@{ub}

    · Ensure  you  have  configured  the drive in which you wish to
      use   the  Mac  disk  by  Mount  ing  it.  The  device  names
      correspond  to  the  device  names  given  by  Commodore. For
      example,  MAC0:  is the Mac device name corresponding to DF0:
      and MAC1: is the Mac device name corresponding to DF1:.
    · Avoid file names longer than 25 characters.
    · Make  sure  you  do  not mix disk types and format types. For
      example,  do  not  do  a low density format on a high density
      disk  or  visa  versa.  Do  not  try  to  read a high density
      formatted disk in a low density drive.
    · Ensure  the  file  formats  you  want to use between both the
      Amiga  program  and  the  Mac  program  are  compatible.  For
      example,  an  Amiga Final Copy file is not readable by an Mac
      WordPerfect wordprocessor.
    · Should  you  exhibit  read  or  write errors with no specific
      pattern,  try  cleaning  the  floppy  drive heads of both the
      Amiga and Mac computers.
    · If  you  are  running  from  a copy of the product disk and a
      utility  appears  not  to run or run correctly, make sure the
      disk name is called ``CrossMAC''
    · The  easiest  way  to  check an Mac disk from the Amiga is to
      run   the   DiskChk   program  included  with  CrossMAC.  The
      following is a list of most of the CrossMAC error codes.
    · Some  directory  utilities  can  not  handle filenames longer
      than  30  characters.  The  directory utility may display the
      file  but  any  operation which tries to access the file will
      fail.  To  fix  the  problem rename the file within Workbench
      and reduce the number of filename characters.
    · Workbench  will  not  properly  display  icons  for Mac files
      with  filename  lengths greater than 25 characters. The icons
      displayed  are  the  Workbench  default  icon  instead of the
      CrossMAC generated icons.
    · Finder  information  is transferred by using the comment. For
      CLI,  the  COM  or  CLONE switch for the copy command must be
      used.  For  Dir Utility programs make sure that they copy the
      comment.
    · The  easiest  way  to  check an Mac disk from the Amiga is to
      run   the   DiskChk   program  included  with  CrossMAC.  The
      following is a list of most of the DiskChk error codes.


